1 (2) Sealing the eviction case court file is in the interests of
2 justice and those interests are not outweighed by the public’s
3 interest in knowing about the contents of the eviction case court file,
4 after considering, without limitation, the following factors:
5 (I) Circumstances beyond the control of the tenant that
6 led to the eviction;
7 (II) Other extenuating circumstances under which the
8 order of eviction was granted; and
9 (III) The amount of time that has elapsed between the
10 granting of the order of eviction and the filing of the motion to seal
11 the eviction case court file. For the purposes of this subparagraph,
12 if the filing of the motion to seal the eviction case court file occurs
13 more than 1 year after the date on which the eviction order is
14 entered, there is a presumption that sealing the eviction case court
15 file is in the interests of justice and those interests are not
16 outweighed by the public’s interest in knowing about the contents
17 of the eviction case court file unless the presumption is rebutted by
18 clear and convincing evidence to the contrary.
19 4. If the court orders the eviction case court file sealed pursuant
20 to this section, all proceedings recounted in the eviction case court
21 file shall be deemed never to have occurred.
22 5. Except as otherwise provided in this subsection, a notice to
23 surrender must not be made available for public inspection by any
24 person or governmental entity, including, without limitation, by a
25 sheriff or constable. This subsection does not:
26 (a) Apply to a notice to surrender which has been filed with a
27 court and which is part of an eviction case court file that has not
28 been sealed pursuant to this section.
29 (b) Prohibit the service of a notice to surrender pursuant to NRS
30 40.280, and such service of a notice to surrender shall be deemed
31 not to constitute making the notice to surrender available for public
32 inspection as described in this subsection.
33 6. As used in this section:
34 (a) “COVID-19 emergency” means the period of time:
35 (1) Beginning on March 12, 2020, the date on which the
36 Governor issued the Declaration of Emergency for COVID-19; and
37 (2) Ending on the date on which the Governor terminates the
38 emergency described in the Declaration [May 20, 2022].
39 (b) “Eviction case court file” means all records relating to an
40 action for summary eviction which are maintained by the court,
41 including, without limitation, the affidavit of complaint and any
42 other pleadings, proof of service, findings of the court, any order
43 made on motion as provided in Nevada Rules of Civil Procedure,
44 Justice Court Rules of Civil Procedure and local rules of practice
